commit.message: moving the options scanning to the start of initialize() didn't seem to work?
somehow I crossed the beams and ended up with a hybrid of older code and HEAD?
move the option handling to BEFORE I start initializing various scratchfiles
add the -V command line option (prints the version & the version comment)
the patch to add c99 syntax flipped the two string args in amatch(), which stopped find from working
in execl, use NULL, not 0L; in the main loop/duff's device, make E_EDIT a label to explicitly nothing (instead of '1' by itself, which makes clang unhappy)
add a patch (via Pascal Jaeger) to reprototype everything so that clang 16 and it's ilk won't throw up all over the source code
when checking where manpages go, default AC_PREFIX before searching for .../share/man
on windows, _findfirst() returns -1 if no match
don't forget to va_end() our valist before logger() finishes
bug: wasn't restoring magic when a local search failed
in ntoa, don't forget to null-terminate the number
bugfixes and enhancements := another release
implement :r !cmd (from https://github.com/pmarin)

1. Use -R for readonly (-r is traditional recovery mode)2. If a unknown command line option is passed, stop processing the command line and pop up an error message3. initialize exit_now (bug with :<DEL> or :<ESC> making levee immediately exit w/o saving)
1. when freeing a glob structure, zero it after globfree() 2. if a workfile isn't provided to os_cmdopen, use /dev/null
if we're using the libc glob(), make sure to turn off GLOB_APPEND in cases where gl_pathc == 0

Cache the # of lines of actual content displayed on the screen so
I can use it for positioning information when I do movement commands
that want to know about end of content instead of end of screen (the M
command, for example)

commit.message: Show a error message when the command is not found
version 4.0; not get the 'a' patch release

3 fixes; f<x> was not erroring when <x> couldn't be found; F<x> was also not working; tags in vi mode weren't reliably working because the whole findbound logic was assuming that it would be called from exec mode
streamline writeline() by pushing all of the buffering into display.c & the os interface layer
change SOFT_EOL define to USCD_COMPAT, because that's the main reason I'd want to treat \r as a eol
ugh; had a print/f/ instead of a print/s/ in an error message
